   <text xml:lang="en">
      <front>
         <div type="cover">
            <head><title type="main">
                  <hi rend="bold"><rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">JUANA
                           MARIA</persName></rs></hi></title>
               <title type="sub"><hi rend="bold"><rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">The
                           Lone Woman of San Nicholas Island</persName></rs></hi></title></head>
            <byline><hi rend="bold">by <persName type="author" key="#gma">Maynard Geiger</persName>,
                  O.F.M., PH.D.</hi></byline>
         </div>
         <div type="titlepage">
            <head><title><supplied>[...]</supplied>
                  <hi rend="bold"><date notBefore="1853" notAfter="1835"
                  >1835-1853</date></hi></title></head>
            <p><supplied>[...]</supplied></p>
            <p>Published by the <orgName type="publisher" key="#serrashop">Serra Shop OLD
                  MISSION</orgName>, <placeName type="city" key="#ci_sb">Santa Barbara</placeName>,
                  <placeName type="state" key="#st_cal">California</placeName></p>
         </div>
      </front>
      <body>
         <div type="excerpt">
            <p><span type="trope" n="5"><span type="trope" n="4">Few events in the history of early
                        <placeName type="city" key="#ci_sb">Santa Barbara</placeName> caused a
                     greater stir and sensation than the discovery in <date when="1853">1853</date>
                     of <rs><persName type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">an Indian
                        woman</persName></rs> on <placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">San Nicolas
                        Island</placeName> who had lived there alone for <rs><date notBefore="1835"
                           notAfter="1853" cert="high">eighteen years</date></rs>. And few events in
                     Santa Barbara's long colorful history have engaged people's imagination and
                     interest as much as the almost incredible story of <rs><persName
                           type="nativeamerican" key="#lw">Juana Maria</persName></rs>. Had this
                     story been written as fiction it would have been rejected. But the story is
                     true. <rs><persName type="group" key="#jru; #aji; #sanchez; #misfats">The
                           Franciscan padres of Mission Santa Barbara</persName></rs> were involved
                     in her discovery.</span></span> Today they are involved in telling her
               story.</p>
            <p><placeName type="island" key="#i_sn">San Nicolas Island</placeName> lies out in
                  <placeName type="region" key="#re_pacific">the Pacific</placeName> about seventy
               miles from <placeName type="city" key="#ci_sp">San Pedro</placeName>. It is nine
               miles long and three and a half miles wide. It had been inhabited by <rs><orgName
                     type="nativeamericantribes" key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">Indians</orgName></rs>
               from the earliest times. In <date when="1811">1811</date>
               <rs><name type="ship" key="#sh_charon">a ship</name></rs> belonging to <orgName
                  key="#bp">Pope and Boardman</orgName> of <placeName type="city" key="#ci_bo"
                  >Boston</placeName>, brought about thirty <orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                  key="#natam_kodiak">Kodiaks</orgName> from <placeName type="state"
                  key="#re_russam">Russian Alaska</placeName> to <placeName type="island"
                  key="#i_sn">San Nicolas Island</placeName> to hunt otter and seal.</p>
            <p>They were left there with provisions to be picked up again <rs><date when="1812">in a
                     year</date></rs> and <rs><name type="ship" key="#sh_charon">the
                  ship</name></rs> sailed further south. Meanwhile[,] a feud broke out between
                     <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes" key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">the native
                     Indians</orgName></rs> and the <orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                  key="#natam_kodiak">Kodiaks</orgName>. The majority of <rs><orgName
                     type="nativeamericantribes" key="#natam_NicolenoTongva">the native
                     men</orgName></rs> were killed by <rs><orgName type="nativeamericantribes"
                     key="#natam_kodiak">the newcomers</orgName></rs> [...]</p>
         </div>
      </body>
